br&gt;&lt;/=\r\nfont&gt;&lt;font size=3D&quot;3&quot; color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font c=\r\nolor=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;div align=3D&quot;LEFT&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=\r\n=3D&quot;3&quot; color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;Now question is, can an average h=\r\numan being &quot;know&quot; this mysterious and all pervading force? Knowin=\r\ng implies understanding. Clearly no. Then how does one interact with such a=\r\n thing? One way is to consider\n everything, and I mean EVERYTHING from livi=\r\nng to non-living, as a manifestation of that force and thus learn to love t=\r\nhe same unconditionally without expecting anything in return. No wonder suc=\r\nh unconditional love is not easy. It needs tremendous effort to change our =\r\nown conditioning of the mind, and work on our inherent biases and prejudice=\r\ns. That is what the=A0 aim of sadhana is, in my view. To work on oneself, t=\r\no make one ready to be able to unconditionally love everything. The greater=\r\n number of entities one can love unconditionally, that much little bit clos=\r\ner one can come to interacting with the truly infinite. And those few rare =\r\nhuman beings who can love a whole universe unconditionally, are possibly th=\r\ne closest to this supreme and unknowable force. In common language, we call=\r\n them Rishis. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;font size=3D&quot;3&quot; color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;V=\r\nerdana&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;div align=3D&quot;LEFT&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=3D&quot;3&quot; color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; f=\r\nace=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;I like all forms of\n Deities, for I find something beautifu=\r\nl in everyone of them. And I also like the One behind forms, which is so pe=\r\nrfectly transcendental that it cannot be comprehended ever. It&#39;s like t=\r\nhe surface area of the fine tip of a needle, or the gap between the two bre=\r\naths, or the millionth part of a single hair, or the endless-ness of space,=\r\n or the bottomless well of stillness in the mind at certain points in medit=\r\nation. The only thing that stops me from getting a better understanding the=\r\n grandeur of=A0 this formless entity are the limitations of my own mind and=\r\n body, that I have acquired over millions of births. That is why Sadhana. T=\r\no slowly gnaw away at my own mind, to be better able to appreciate this end=\r\nless, nameless entity. G_d. &lt;font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;font size=3D&quot;3&quot; =\r\ncolor=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=\r\n=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;div align=3D&quot;LEFT&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=3D&quot;3&quot; color=3D&quot;#0000=\r\n00&quot; face=3D&quot;Verdana&quot;&gt;I do not\n believe in Moksha. What is Moksha? No rebirt=\r\nh? If the Universe itself gets born over and over and over, if Rama and Krs=\r\nhna come back at every cycle, who am I to demand that I should not get born=\r\n? Infact, when a person proverbially finishes off his/her karmas, they mere=\r\nly go to another plane in this Universe and stay there for eons of time, si=\r\nnce time anyway moves very, very slowly in different realms. But then, if t=\r\nhis force so wants, it can send back any of the souls from any of the realm=\r\ns to any of the other realms to serve a certain function. And if a soul sta=\r\nys in a certain higher realm and in forced to take rebirth again, the seeds=\r\n of the karmas - which never really die off - are=A0 watered again by the e=\r\nnvironment of birth and they sprout into saplings. And this may go even bey=\r\nond one cycle of creation. Else why would Krshna and Arjuna fight the very =\r\nsame enemies that they had been fighting in the past cycle of creation? Mah=\r\nabharata says so. I\n believe it. &lt;/